The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, May 07, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, May 6: The Gujarat government-backed Sardar Sarovar Narmada Nigam Ltd is planning to prepay high-cost 20-year bonds to save about Rs 6,100 crore. The move will slash returns to a few lakh investors. To get the investors consent, the company has called a meeting on May 28 as the 17 per cent interest bonds, issued in January 1994, did not provide for pre-mature redemption by the issuer. In case it fails to get the consent of bond-holders for the early redemption, the company would have to bear a burden of Rs 7,800 crore till 2014, said managing director S. K. Mohapatra.																								 Mumbai, May 6: LNM group chairman L. N. Mittal has picked up a 0.43 per cent stake, or 31.10 lakh shares, in ICICI Bank. The London-based steel baron acquired these shares on April 21.																								 Mumbai, May 6: South Korean major LG today launched its FMCG subsidiary, LG Care, in India through a licensee agreement with India Household amp; Healthcare Ltd.																								 Mumbai, May 6: Bombay High Court today approved the merger of Ashok Leyland Finance Ltd with IndusInd Bank.																								 Calcutta, May 6: West Bengal Small Industries Development Corporation Ltd plans to improve infrastructure at the existing 34 industrial and commercial estates to promote small-scale units in the state, said Hari Ramulu, managing director.
